motivation is a pitfall. stop relying on it and just bruteforce yourself to do a page or even a set amount of sentences a day. The dopamine is meant to kick in after you do something as a reward, not as an incentive to do something as payment for that feeling. You can help reqire yourself by setting a quota then rewarding yourself with a treat then increasing the next day's quota. if you have more to add, table it for next day's quota and you'll always have something to write off the bat. From what i've read in self-help and interviews with writers. you just have to do it ignoring how you feel about it. if you are a writer you must write.

I wouldn't put it any other way. You'd be surprised how indifferent to emotion/mood you can be if you try. It's simply amazing. we as individuals can accomplish when we put ourselves to it. people talk about willpower like it's some energy resource of magic action juice but real willpower is a will to power. Cold, clinical, indifferent, decisive. There's a time and a place for feeling but when there's something you need to do (and finishing a story is a definite 'need' if you respect, let alone enjoy the art of writing). I suggest reading stereotypically sigma grindset shit to put yourself in this headspace. I flip to certain parts of my copy of Aurelius' Meditations I think apply the most to my life.
